>>>>> ritter@cactus.org (Terry Ritter) (TR) writes:

>> Nonsense.  My proposal is that, given the ciphertext, the user
>> would be required to make it plain.  This means that there would
>> be a responsibility to log old *keys*, not conversations.

TR>  RSA gives public-key capability, but is slow.  Typically, a
TR>  "public key" cryptosystem will only pass a session key under RSA,
TR>  and then use a faster private-key system to encipher the data.
TR>  Logging the session key would give the ability to recover the
TR>  plaintext at a later date.

So that would make it a criminal offense to have a disk crash?
